## Data Modeling

### Data Model Structure
The dataset required minimal modeling as it consisted of a single flat table. However, we created a star-schema-like structure with calculated measures for analytical purposes.

### Key Measures Created

```dax
// ===== CORE METRICS =====
Total_Employees = COUNT('Remote_Work_Fact'[Employee_ID])


Avg Stress Score = AVERAGEX('Sheet1', [Stress_Num])

// ===== MENTAL HEALTH =====
Employees with Conditions = 
CALCULATE(COUNT('Remote_Work_Fact'[Employee_ID]),
    'Remote_Work_Fact'[Mental_Health_Condition] <> "None")
)

// ===== WELL-BEING METRICS =====
Avg Social Isolation = AVERAGE('Remote_Work_Fact'[Social_Isolation_Rating])

Avg Work-Life Balance = AVERAGE(Remote_Work_Fact[Work_Life_Balance_Rating])

High Stress % = DIVIDE(CALCULATE(COUNT('Remote_Work_Fact'[Employee_ID]), 'Remote_Work_Fact'[Stress_Level] = "High"),
    COUNT('Remote_Work_Fact'[Employee_ID]))

// ===== SATISFACTION METRICS =====
Satisfied with Remote % = 
DIVIDE(CALCULATE
(COUNT('Remote_Work_Fact'[Employee_ID]),
        'Remote_Work_Fact'[Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work] = "Satisfied"),COUNT(Remote_Work_Fact[Employee_ID]))

Avg Company Support = AVERAGE(Remote_Work_Fact[Company_Support_for_Remote_Work])


